intro:
What if you don't want to **hide** an item per-player but **change** how it looks? That's [bindings](wiki:bindings).

A binding is a `(rules, props)` pair attached to an item. When the rules pass, the props **override** the item's normal fields. Different players see different versions of the same slot - same item, different material, name, lore, click handler.

```
items = [
  {
    slot = 4
    material = STONE
    name = "&7Standard"
    bindings = [
      {
        rules { permission = "vip" }
        props {
          material = DIAMOND
          name = "&aVIP exclusive"
        }
      }
    ]
  }
]
```

No permission -> sees STONE "Standard". With `vip` permission -> sees DIAMOND "VIP exclusive". Same slot, two faces.

Bindings are checked in array order, **first match wins**. Multiple bindings = a tier system:

```
bindings = [
  {
    rules { permission = "admin" }
    props { name = "&cAdmin" }
  }
  {
    rules { permission = "vip" }
    props { name = "&aVIP" }
  }
]
```

`props` accepts any item-scope key (material, name, lore, click, count, ...) - it's a partial item override.

**Goal:** add a `bindings` array on the item with one binding that swaps `material` to `DIAMOND` for players with the `vip` permission.

